---
import Site from '../layouts/Site.astro';
---

<Site title="Projects — Łukasz Żyła" current="projects">
  <section class="projects">
    <h1 class="sr-only">Projects</h1>

    <article class="project">
      <h2 class="project-title">#OtwartePaństwo</h2>
      <p class="project-lead">
        A civic-tech platform that gathers scattered official journals into one
        searchable, citable source of binding law.
      </p>
      <p>
        In Poland a law does not bind the moment parliament passes it — only once
        it is promulgated. Under Art. 88 of the Constitution, entry into force is
        conditional on publication. Since 1 January 2012 the official journals
        (<em>Dziennik Ustaw</em>, <em>Monitor Polski</em> and dozens of
        institutional and regional gazettes) are no longer printed at all: the
        electronic edition is the sole authentic source of the law in force, and
        the date of online publication is the date the act legally exists.
      </p>
      <p>
        #OtwartePaństwo aggregates and standardizes these dispersed publications —
        each with its own format, numbering and layout — into a single,
        full-text-searchable corpus that you can quote from and link to precisely.
      </p>
      <p class="project-note">
        It treats “the moment a rule becomes binding” as data: promulgation dates,
        journal positions and effective dates become queryable rather than buried
        in PDFs.
      </p>
    </article>

    <article class="project">
      <h2 class="project-title">
        <a href="https://ktorzadzi.pl" target="_blank" rel="noopener">ktorzadzi.pl&nbsp;↗</a>
      </h2>
      <p class="project-lead">
        The first Polish app to visualize the power network between politics and
        business, built entirely from official registers.
      </p>
      <p>
        Ties between public figures and companies are technically public but
        scattered across separate databases. ktorzadzi.pl pulls from official
        sources — the National Court Register (KRS) and the Central Register of
        Business Activity (CEIDG) — cross-references them and reconstructs the
        relationships: who sat on which board, where and when, and how people and
        institutions connect.
      </p>
      <p>
        It was built by the Media&nbsp;3.0 foundation, inspired by and developed
        in cooperation with Spain's
        <a href="https://civio.es/poder/que-es-quien-manda/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Fundación Civio&nbsp;↗</a>
        and its <em>Quién manda</em> (“Who governs”) project — a map of power that
        ran from 2014 to 2023 and became a European reference point for this kind
        of accountability journalism.
      </p>
      <p class="project-note">
        The innovation was methodological: turning raw, disconnected public
        registers into a navigable graph of influence, quotable back to its
        official source.
      </p>
    </article>

    <article class="project">
      <h2 class="project-title">
        <a href="https://jaturzadze.pl" target="_blank" rel="noopener">jaturzadze.pl&nbsp;↗</a>
      </h2>
      <p class="project-lead">
        Local-government budgets, made legible — an app that processes and
        visualizes municipal financial data.
      </p>
      <p>
        Local budgets are published, but as spreadsheets few residents can read.
        jaturzadze.pl ingests that financial data and turns it into clear
        visualizations of where public money comes from and where it goes.
      </p>
      <p>
        The prototype won 3rd place at Poland's first government open-data
        hackathon (Ministry of Digital Affairs, 2016), built with the
        Media&nbsp;3.0 / SAP team, and was later revisited in a 2025 edition.
      </p>
      <p class="project-note">
        A recurring theme across these projects: the data already exists and is
        public — the work is making it usable.
      </p>
    </article>

    <article class="project">
      <h2 class="project-title">Aplikacja Parlament / Sejm</h2>
      <p class="project-lead">
        The first app to process live data from the Polish Sejm — parliamentary
        work turned into an accessible, real-time feed.
      </p>
      <p>
        Votes, sittings, MPs and legislative motions were hard to follow as they
        happened. The app captured the Sejm's data stream and rendered it as a
        readable feed, in cooperation with the Chancellery of the Sejm
        (Kancelaria Sejmu).
      </p>
      <p class="project-note">
        It anticipated what is now taken for granted — parliamentary transparency
        as a live, machine-readable data source rather than static minutes.
      </p>
    </article>

    <article class="project">
      <h2 class="project-title">
        <a href="https://wojaczek.vercel.app/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Śladami Wojaczka&nbsp;↗</a>
      </h2>
      <p class="project-lead">
        An audio-literary, augmented-reality walk through the poetry of Rafał
        Wojaczek (1945–1971), the Silesian <em>poète maudit</em>.
      </p>
      <p>
        The app anchors Wojaczek's poems to the real places he lived and wrote in,
        combining augmented reality (AR), an audio layer and location-based
        storytelling, with text mining of his corpus to surface recurring motifs.
        It doubles as cultural-heritage archiving — preserving and re-presenting a
        body of work tied to a specific city and landscape.
      </p>
      <p class="project-note">
        Literary heritage as something you walk through: the city becomes the
        interface, and the poems appear where they belong.
      </p>
    </article>

    <article class="project">
      <h2 class="project-title">Finnegans Work <span class="badge">in progress</span></h2>
      <p class="project-lead">
        A research project mining James Joyce's <em>Finnegans Wake</em> for
        pattern and meaning across its many languages.
      </p>
      <p>
        <em>Finnegans Wake</em> is written in a dense, portmanteau idiom that
        braids together dozens of languages and resists linear reading. Finnegans
        Work applies text mining and semantic analysis, together with experiments
        in neural networks and NLP, to detect patterns and help decode the book's
        multilingual layers.
      </p>
      <p class="project-note">
        The name is a nod to the <em>Wake</em> itself — treating one of
        literature's hardest texts as a computational-linguistics problem, without
        pretending to “solve” it.
      </p>
    </article>
  </section>
</Site>

<style is:global>
  .projects {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 44px;
  }
  .project { max-width: 62ch; }
  .project-title {
    font-size: 24px;
    font-weight: 500;
    line-height: 1.25;
    color: var(--ink);
    margin: 0 0 12px;
    display: flex;
    align-items: baseline;
    gap: 12px;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
  }
  .project-title a { color: var(--ink); text-decoration: none; }
  .project-lead {
    font-size: 19px;
    line-height: 1.55;
    color: var(--ink);
    margin: 0 0 14px;
  }
  .project p {
    font-size: 17px;
    line-height: 1.62;
    color: var(--body);
    margin: 0 0 12px;
  }
  .project p:last-child { margin: 0; }
  .project-note {
    color: var(--label);
    font-style: italic;
  }
  .project .badge {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 11px;
    font-style: normal;
    font-weight: 500;
    letter-spacing: 0.12em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--muted);
    border: 1px solid var(--rule);
    border-radius: 999px;
    padding: 2px 9px;
    white-space: nowrap;
  }
  /* Link highlight spójny z resztą strony */
  .project a {
    background-image: linear-gradient(var(--hl), var(--hl));
    background-repeat: no-repeat;
    background-position: 0 92%;
    background-size: 0% 0.3em;
    transition: background-size 0.28s ease;
    border-radius: 1px;
  }
  .project a:hover { background-size: 100% 0.3em; }
</style>
